facts: The Moon is Earth's only natural satellite.
The Moon is the fifth largest satellite in the Solar System.
The Moon's diameter is about 3,474 kilometers, roughly a quarter of Earth's.
The Moon's gravity is about one-sixth (16.7%) of Earth's gravity.
The Moon has no significant atmosphere, which means no weather and no protection from solar radiation.
The lack of atmosphere means the sky on the Moon is always black, even during the day.
The temperature on the Moon ranges from a scorching 127°C in sunlight to a frigid -173°C in darkness.
The Moon is in synchronous rotation with Earth, meaning it rotates on its axis in the same time it takes to orbit Earth.
Because of synchronous rotation, we always see the same side of the Moon, known as the "near side."
The side we don't see from Earth is called the "far side," not the "dark side."
The leading theory of the Moon's origin is the Giant-Impact Hypothesis.
The Giant-Impact Hypothesis suggests the Moon formed from debris after a Mars-sized object named Theia collided with Earth.
Only 12 people, all American men from the Apollo program, have walked on the Moon.
The dark, flat plains on the Moon are called "maria" (Latin for seas), which were formed by ancient volcanic eruptions.
The lighter, cratered areas on the Moon are called "highlands" or "terrae."
The Moon's surface is covered in a layer of fine dust and rocky debris called regolith.
The Moon experiences "moonquakes," caused by the Earth's gravitational pull.
The Moon is slowly moving away from Earth at a rate of about 3.8 centimeters per year.
A lunar day (from one sunrise to the next) lasts about 29.5 Earth days.
The footprints left by the Apollo astronauts will likely remain for millions of years due to the lack of wind or water.
The Moon has water ice, primarily located in permanently shadowed craters at its poles.
The crater with the highest concentration of surface ice is Shackleton crater at the south pole.
The term "Blue Moon" refers to the second full moon in a single calendar month.
A "lunar eclipse" occurs when the Earth passes directly between the Sun and Moon, casting a shadow on the Moon.
A "solar eclipse" occurs when the Moon passes between the Sun and Earth.
The Moon's gravitational pull is the primary cause of Earth's ocean tides.
The largest crater on the Moon is the South Pole-Aitken Basin, which is also one of the largest in the solar system.
The Moon has no magnetic field of its own, but some of its surface rocks are magnetized.
The first spacecraft to reach the Moon was the Soviet Union's Luna 2 in 1959.
The first photos of the far side of the Moon were taken by the Soviet Luna 3 probe in 1959.
The material returned from the Moon by Apollo missions totaled 382 kilograms.
The far side of the Moon has a much thicker crust and fewer maria than the near side.
The official name for the Moon is just "the Moon."
The study of the Moon's geology is called selenology.
The tallest mountain on the Moon, Mons Huygens, is about 4,700 meters high.
The Moon appears the same size as the Sun in the sky because it is 400 times smaller but also 400 times closer to Earth.
Helium-3, a potential future fuel for fusion reactors, is thought to be abundant in lunar regolith.
The Moon has no rings.
The Soviet Union's Lunokhod 1 was the first remote-controlled rover on another celestial body.
The last person to walk on the Moon was Eugene Cernan in 1972.
The Artemis program aims to return humans to the Moon in the 2020s.
A full Moon is about 14 times brighter than a half Moon (first quarter).
The distance from the Earth to the Moon is, on average, about 384,400 kilometers.
The word "lunatic" is derived from the Latin word "lunaticus," meaning "moonstruck."
China's Chang'e 4 mission was the first to successfully land on the far side of the Moon.
India's Chandrayaan-3 was the first mission to successfully land near the lunar south pole.
The age of the Moon is estimated to be around 4.51 billion years old.
The rocks brought back from the Moon are older than any rocks found on Earth's surface.
The flags planted on the Moon by Apollo astronauts have likely been bleached white by solar radiation.
It takes light about 1.3 seconds to travel from the Moon to Earth.
The Moon has a very thin layer of gases called an exosphere, not a true atmosphere.
The scientific name for moon dust is "lunar regolith."
The South Pole-Aitken Basin on the far side is about 2,500 kilometers in diameter.
Astronaut Alan Shepard hit a golf ball on the Moon during the Apollo 14 mission.
The Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) used in later Apollo missions had a top speed of about 18 km/h.
The Apollo 11 landing site is named "Tranquility Base."
The Moon reflects only about 12% of the sunlight that hits it.
There are still three Lunar Roving Vehicles left on the Moon from the Apollo missions.
The Moon is slowly causing the Earth's rotation to slow down, a process called tidal braking.
A "supermoon" occurs when a full Moon coincides with its closest approach to Earth (perigee).
A "micromoon" occurs when a full Moon coincides with its farthest point from Earth (apogee).
The Moon's core is likely small, metallic, and partly molten.
Without the Moon, Earth would wobble more on its axis, leading to extreme climate changes.
Some craters near the lunar poles are in permanent shadow and haven't seen sunlight for billions of years.
The first living things to circle the Moon were tortoises and other lifeforms aboard the Soviet Zond 5 mission.
The term "selenography" refers to the mapping of the Moon's surface features.
The Apollo 15 mission discovered the "Genesis Rock," one of the oldest rocks ever found.
The Moon does not have tectonic plates like Earth does.
The force of gravity on the Moon is not uniform due to mass concentrations ("mascons") beneath the large maria.
The Moon completes one orbit around the Earth approximately every 27.3 days.
The cycle of lunar phases (e.g., from full moon to full moon) takes about 29.5 days.
The Apollo 1 command module is on display at the Kennedy Space Center.
The Moon can appear red during a total lunar eclipse, known as a "Blood Moon."
Early astronomers thought the maria were actual seas, hence the name.
The first detailed map of the Moon was created by Giovanni Riccioli in 1651.
The Apollo 12 astronauts retrieved parts from the Surveyor 3 probe that had landed two years earlier.
The Moon has no liquid water on its surface.
The chemical composition of Moon rocks is very similar to Earth's mantle.
The youngest craters on the Moon are a few million years old, while the oldest are billions.
"Lunar swirls" are mysterious, bright patterns on the Moon's surface that are not well understood.
The first commercial mission to successfully land on the Moon was Intuitive Machines' IM-1 in 2024.
The word "month" is derived from the word "moon."
A small part of the Moon's interior is still molten.
The Lunar Library, a digital archive of human knowledge, was sent to the Moon on the Beresheet lander.
The Apollo Guidance Computer was one of the first computers to use integrated circuits.
The total mass of the Moon is about 1.2% of the Earth's mass.
The Moon's orbital plane is tilted by about 5.1 degrees with respect to Earth's orbital plane.
There are no known active volcanoes on the Moon today.
The Moon has been visited by spacecraft from more than five different countries.
The average density of the Moon is 3.34 g/cm³, much less than Earth's 5.51 g/cm³.
The oldest rocks collected from the Moon are about 4.46 billion years old.
The "Man in the Moon" is an example of pareidolia, the tendency to see familiar patterns in random data.
The first woman to have a planned mission to the Moon is Christina Koch, part of the Artemis II crew.
The Moon is a differentiated body, meaning it has a crust, mantle, and core.
During the Apollo era, astronauts were quarantined after returning from the Moon to prevent "lunar germs."
The Treaty on Outer Space of 1967 states that no nation can claim ownership of the Moon.
The soil on the Moon is electrostatically charged by solar radiation.
The Moon's crust is thinner on the near side and thicker on the far side.
